Check if $X$ is independent of $Y$ given $Z$. Provide the steps through your derivations.

\item Consider the random variables $X,Y,Z$ which jointly follow a Gaussian distribution: \\

$$\begin{bmatrix} X \\ Y \\ Z \end{bmatrix} \sim \mathcal{N}\left( \begin{bmatrix}
\mu_x \\ \mu_y \\ \mu_z \\
\end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix}
\Sigma_{xx} & 0 & 0\\
0 & \Sigma_{yy} & 0\\
0 & 0 & \Sigma_{zz}\\
\end{bmatrix} \right)$$

Check if $X$ is independent of $Y$ given $Z$ and provide the steps through your derivations.

\item Let $X,Y,Z,U$ be random variables following PMFs $P_x, P_y, P_z, P_u$. Prove that the 5 separoid axioms for the random variables hold:

\begin{enumerate}
\item Redundancy X \indep Y 
\item Symmetry
\item (left) contraction
\item (left) weak union
\item (left) decomposition
\end{enumerate}
(5$\times$1 pts)
\end{enumerate}

\begin{gradedsolution}
\begin{enumerate}
\item 
\item Answer: show that the conditional PDFs are the marginals regardless of the value of the conditioning variable.
\item 

\begin{enumerate}
\item Redundancy: 
\[ P_x(X,Y|X) = \frac{P(X,Y|X)}{P(X)} = \frac{P(Y|X)P(X)}{P(X)}]\]
marginalize over X:

\[ P_x(X,Y|X) = \sum_X P(Y|X)=P(Y)\]
\item Symmetry: 
\item (left) contraction
\item (left) weak union
\item (left) decomposition
\end{enumerate}
(5$\times$1 pts)
\end{enumerate}

\end{gradedsolution}


